{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778261019,"nonce":"Q689MWaCCRF9wlvEEO2izUJsVyQ=","message":"**Exploring a potential next-phase programme: regulator-coupling and biomechanical decoupling** (not committed to running this chain — documenting the direction for decision-making).\n\n---\n\n### The headline puzzle\n\nThree numbers disagree: (i) C\u0026S 2019 reports ~+10–15% empirical Δv in humans under unpredictable curl perturbations; (ii) the corrected analytical H∞ Riccati on the C\u0026S regime predicts +1.0% (or +10.8% on the rlrmp regime with the C\u0026S cost schedule); (iii) trained flavor-B GRUs give Δv ≈ −25% at the group mean. All three use different reach geometries, different cost schedules, and different disturbance classes.\n\n### The reframing: regulator vs tracker\n\nThe right cut is not \"linear vs nonlinear\" — it is **regulator vs tracker**. A Riccati regulator `u_t = -K_t·x_t` uses the same gain to drive the nominal trajectory and to reject perturbations; it cannot independently scale feedforward drive and feedback gain. An RNN with a hidden-state feedforward channel `u_t = u_ff(t) − K_local(t)·(x_t − x_nom(t))` can, in principle, lower stiffness without lowering baseline drive — \"decoupling.\" Gemini's central claim is that this is what trained GRUs do. Codex identifies several confounds (eval geometry, cost schedule, adversary class) that need ruling out first.\n\n### The proposed 9-stage chain (stage 0 through 8, then 9)\n\n- **Stage 0** — LQG vs H∞ Riccati replication on C\u0026S regime (03a148a): establish clean analytical ground truth.\n- **Stage 1** — Eval-pipeline audit (4469cae): fix 0.5 m vs 15 cm reach mismatch; re-evaluate all empirical Δv.\n- **Stage 2** — Linear regulator + linear tracker baselines (d448c9d): the decoupling acid test.\n- **Stage 3** — Cost-schedule sweep (t/N)^α (6ec6b19): isolate schedule contribution.\n- **Stage 4** — Full-state ε adversary class (020a65b): align training disturbance with C\u0026S Eq. 13.\n- **Stage 5** — H∞ Riccati teacher distillation (db35426): architecture capability check.\n- **Stage 6** — Capacity-restricted RNN ablation (cf56e1e): rank-1 to full GRU under matched adversary.\n- **Stage 7** — Two-link arm with 6-muscle activation dynamics (ac06736): biomechanical coupling test.\n- **Stage 8** — Decoupling decomposition analysis (8fcb6c7): variance partition u_ff + K_local·error + residual.\n- **Stage 9** — Constrained-RNN regulator (f7b1b17): force u_t = K_RNN(h_t)·x_t, no u_ff.\n\nSupporting analyses: bimodal-replicate clustering (daa48c8), adversary strategy verification prerequisite (89891ab).\n\n### 4-cell discriminator (stage 2 is the critical one)\n\n| | Linear regulator | Linear tracker |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Gemini (decoupling real)** | Δv \u003e 0 | Δv ≈ 0 |\n| **Codex (confounds dominate)** | Δv unpredictable | Δv unpredictable |\n| **Both wrong** | Both converge to same Δv | (controller class doesn't matter) |\n\n### Predicted-outcomes table\n\n| Stage | Gemini (decoupling-is-real) | Codex (underdetermined) | Would falsify both |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 (eval audit) | trained Δv stays ≈ −25% after geometry fix | trained Δv shifts toward zero or positive | trained Δv shifts to −60%+ |\n| 2 (linear reg vs tracker) | regulator +Δv; tracker, RNN ≈ 0 | all four split unpredictably | all four converge to same Δv |\n| 3 (Q-schedule sweep) | RNN Δv flat across α; regulator tracks Riccati | RNN tracks Riccati under matched α | both architectures stay ≈ 0 across all α |\n| 4 (matched ε adversary) | linear reg → +Δv; GRU stays ≈ 0 | linear reg round-trips cleanly; GRU shifts | round-trip identity fails on linear reg |\n| 5 (Riccati distillation) | cloned GRU recovers +Δv | cloned GRU recovers +Δv | cloned GRU stays ≈ 0 |\n| 6 (rank ablation) | smooth shift reg-like → tracker-like | unclear, noisy | flat across rank |\n| 7 (muscle plant) | Δv goes positive in muscle space | Δv stays ≈ 0 | Δv goes more negative |\n| 8 (decomposition) | high u_ff variance in GRU; low in reg | mixed | regulator-like decomp in all networks |\n| 9 (constraint) | constrained GRU recovers +Δv | constrained GRU still ≈ 0 | Δv recovers but task loss degrades |\n\n### Cross-cutting implication for future training-method comparisons\n\nIf the chain runs, every future training-method comparison should include both a linear regulator and a linear tracker as baselines — not just a nominal LQR. The regulator/tracker distinction is the operative axis, not the linear/nonlinear one.\n\n**Status: exploring, not committed.** The chain is ordered by information-gain per unit cost; each stage can halt the programme if its answer is decisive. Stage 1 (eval audit) is the cheapest and most important first step.","files":null}]}